  <h1>Burn Classifications and Prognosis</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by our editorial team &mdash; Medical Documentation &amp; Burn Care. Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <p>The medical classification of burn injuries directly drives both medical prognosis and the legal compensation framework. This guide walks through the depth classification, Total Body Surface Area (TBSA) estimation, healing patterns, and scar evolution over the first 2&ndash;5 years &mdash; the period that matters most for case valuation.</p>

  <h2>Depth classification</h2>

  <p>Burn depth is the primary determinant of healing potential and reconstructive needs. Modern burn medicine recognizes four degrees:</p>

  <h3>1st degree &mdash; superficial</h3>
  <p>Limited to the epidermis (outermost skin layer). Presents as redness and tenderness without blistering. The skin remains intact and intact sensation is preserved. Common in sunburn, brief flame exposure, and very minor scalds.</p>
  <p><strong>Healing:</strong> 3&ndash;7 days, typically without scarring. The injured layer sloughs off and is replaced by normal epidermis from below.</p>
  <p><strong>Legal significance:</strong> Limited unless very large surface area is involved or the burn was accompanied by other trauma. 1st-degree burns are typically excluded from TBSA calculations for damages purposes.</p>

  <h3>2nd degree &mdash; partial thickness</h3>
  <p>Extends into the dermis but does not destroy it completely. Subdivided clinically into:</p>

  <h4>Superficial partial thickness</h4>
  <p>Blistering, very painful, intact pinprick sensation, blanches with pressure (turns white when pressed, then quickly refills with blood). The wound bed is bright red or pink.</p>
  <p><strong>Healing:</strong> 10&ndash;21 days with appropriate wound care, typically with minimal scarring (some pigmentation changes may persist).</p>

  <h4>Deep partial thickness</h4>
  <p>Reduced or absent sensation in central burn (the deeper nerve endings are destroyed), slower or absent blanching, pale or mottled wound bed. May convert to full thickness over the first 48&ndash;72 hours if not appropriately managed.</p>
  <p><strong>Healing:</strong> Often 21&ndash;35+ days; many deep partial-thickness burns are grafted because spontaneous healing produces unacceptable scarring (thick, raised, contracted scars). Hypertrophic scarring is the rule rather than the exception.</p>

  <h3>3rd degree &mdash; full thickness</h3>
  <p>The entire dermis is destroyed, including hair follicles, sweat glands, and nerve endings. The burn appears white, leathery, charred, brown, or waxy. The central wound is typically painless (nerve endings destroyed); pain at the margins comes from partial-thickness areas surrounding the full-thickness core.</p>
  <p><strong>Healing:</strong> Skin grafting is almost always required. Spontaneous healing only occurs from the wound edges via contracture, which causes functional and aesthetic problems if the wound is not grafted promptly.</p>
  <p><strong>Long-term:</strong> Grafted skin is permanently more fragile than original skin, doesn't sweat (impaired thermoregulation), and is at elevated risk of skin cancer. Requires lifetime maintenance.</p>

  <h3>4th degree &mdash; extending to muscle, tendon, or bone</h3>
  <p>The most severe category. Damage extends below the skin into deeper structures. Often associated with high-voltage electrical injury, prolonged flame contact, severe industrial accidents, and immersion-type scalds.</p>
  <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Frequently requires amputation (for severely damaged limbs), complex reconstructive surgery, or free-flap procedures to provide soft-tissue coverage over exposed bone or tendon. Multiple surgical stages over months to years.</p>
  <p><strong>Long-term:</strong> Permanent functional loss is the rule. The damages picture is dominated by limb loss or major functional deficit alongside the burn itself.</p>

  <h2>Total Body Surface Area (TBSA)</h2>

  <p>TBSA is the percentage of body skin affected by 2nd-degree or deeper burns. (1st-degree burns are excluded from TBSA for treatment and damages purposes.) Two methods are commonly used.</p>

  <h3>Rule of Nines</h3>
  <p>Quick field estimation. The adult body is divided into regions of approximately 9% each:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Head and neck: 9%</li>
    <li>Each arm: 9% (4.5% front + 4.5% back)</li>
    <li>Each leg: 18% (9% front + 9% back)</li>
    <li>Front of torso: 18%</li>
    <li>Back of torso: 18%</li>
    <li>Perineum: 1%</li>
  </ul>
  <p>The Rule of Nines is used in pre-hospital and emergency-department settings for quick estimation. It is meaningfully inaccurate for children (whose heads are proportionally larger and legs proportionally smaller) and is typically replaced or adjusted in burn-center documentation.</p>

  <h3>Lund-Browder chart</h3>
  <p>The standard of care in major burn centers. The body is mapped into smaller, anatomically-specific regions with percentages that adjust for age (infant, 1 year, 5 years, 10 years, 15 years, adult). For pediatric burns particularly, the Lund-Browder TBSA differs meaningfully from a Rule-of-Nines estimate.</p>
  <p>For litigation purposes, the Lund-Browder TBSA is the reference. Field-estimate TBSAs should be supplemented with a Lund-Browder calculation in burn-center records.</p>

  <h3>The "palm rule" for irregular burns</h3>
  <p>The patient's own palm (with fingers) represents approximately 1% TBSA. Used for quick estimation of scattered or irregular burns where the Rule of Nines is awkward.</p>

  <h2>TBSA thresholds in burn medicine</h2>

  <p>Several TBSA thresholds drive medical decisions and (indirectly) damages valuation:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>10% TBSA in adults / 5% in children:</strong> Threshold for transfer to a verified burn center per ABA criteria.</li>
    <li><strong>20% TBSA:</strong> IV fluid resuscitation per Parkland or modified Brooke formula becomes necessary.</li>
    <li><strong>40% TBSA:</strong> Substantial mortality risk; multi-organ involvement common.</li>
    <li><strong>60% TBSA:</strong> Historically high mortality; modern burn centers have improved outcomes but morbidity remains severe.</li>
    <li><strong>80% TBSA:</strong> Survival possible at top burn centers but extremely complex course; long-term outcomes shaped by lifetime grafting and reconstruction.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Inhalation injury</h2>

  <p>Inhalation injury &mdash; from breathing hot air, smoke, or toxic combustion products &mdash; is the single largest mortality predictor in burn medicine. It can occur even with relatively modest TBSA. Signs include facial burns, singed nasal hairs, soot in the airway, hoarseness, and stridor. Mechanism includes:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Thermal injury to upper airway (rarely extends below the larynx).</li>
    <li>Chemical injury from smoke particles and toxic gases (carbon monoxide, hydrogen cyanide, oxides of nitrogen).</li>
    <li>Systemic effects from carbon monoxide and hydrogen cyanide.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Survivors of significant inhalation injury commonly have lifelong reactive airway disease, requiring inhaled medications and recurrent hospitalizations. Damages picture includes lifetime pulmonary care.</p>

  <h2>Scar evolution over the first 2&ndash;5 years</h2>

  <p>For litigation purposes, understanding scar evolution is critical. The damages picture is incomplete until scars have matured, which typically takes 18&ndash;24 months minimum. Phases:</p>

  <h3>Acute wound (0&ndash;3 weeks)</h3>
  <p>Wound bed care, grafting if needed, early scar prevention with silicone and compression. The final scar character is not yet predictable.</p>

  <h3>Active scar formation (3 weeks&ndash;6 months)</h3>
  <p>The scar becomes raised, red, and active. Hypertrophic scarring &mdash; where the scar grows thick within the original wound boundaries &mdash; develops in this phase. Pressure garments and silicone are initiated. Active scar management is at its most intensive.</p>

  <h3>Scar maturation (6 months&ndash;2 years)</h3>
  <p>The scar gradually flattens, depigments toward final color, and stabilizes. Contractures (where scar tissue crosses joints and limits motion) become apparent and may require surgical release. The body's final scar character emerges during this phase.</p>

  <h3>Mature scarring (2 years and beyond)</h3>
  <p>The scar is mostly stable. Minor changes can still occur over years, but the bulk of evolution is complete. Reconstructive surgery during this phase aims to refine appearance and function rather than respond to active scar activity.</p>

  <h2>Hypertrophic scarring vs keloid scarring</h2>

  <p>Two related but distinct scar pathologies are important to understand:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Hypertrophic scars</strong> grow thick within the original wound boundaries. Common after burns, particularly in younger patients and pigmented skin. Often improve over years with treatment.</li>
    <li><strong>Keloid scars</strong> grow beyond the original wound boundaries. More common in pigmented skin and certain anatomic sites. Less responsive to treatment; often recur after surgical excision.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>The distinction matters for prognosis: hypertrophic scarring generally improves with steroid injections, laser therapy, and pressure-garment management, while keloid scarring is notoriously difficult to treat and often recurs.</p>

  <h2>Contractures</h2>

  <p>When scar tissue crosses a joint (neck, axilla, elbow, wrist, hand web spaces, knee), the tightening scar can limit joint range of motion. Hand burns produce contractures that affect grip and dexterity; axillary burns limit overhead reach; neck contractures can affect chewing, swallowing, and head movement. Contracture release surgery is among the most common reconstructive procedures in burn practice; major contractures typically need release at intervals over years as the patient grows or as scars re-form.</p>

  <h2>Prognosis by burn severity</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Minor burns (under 10% TBSA, no full thickness, no airway):</strong> Recovery typically complete in 1&ndash;3 months. Minimal long-term sequelae for most patients.</li>
    <li><strong>Moderate burns (10&ndash;25% TBSA, some full thickness):</strong> Recovery measured in months to a year. Significant scarring is the rule; modest functional impact depending on location.</li>
    <li><strong>Severe burns (25&ndash;50% TBSA, substantial full thickness):</strong> Recovery measured in years. Significant scarring and functional impact. Multiple grafting and reconstructive procedures over 5&ndash;10 years post-injury.</li>
    <li><strong>Catastrophic burns (over 50% TBSA, airway involvement, or 4th degree):</strong> Lifetime medical needs. Severe functional and aesthetic impact. PTSD prevalence approaches 50%.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Complications to watch for</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Wound infection</strong> &mdash; the leading cause of mortality in modern burn care.</li>
    <li><strong>Sepsis</strong> &mdash; bloodstream infection; common in extensive burns.</li>
    <li><strong>Pneumonia and respiratory failure</strong> &mdash; especially with inhalation injury.</li>
    <li><strong>Graft loss</strong> &mdash; failure of grafted skin to integrate; requires re-grafting.</li>
    <li><strong>Hypertrophic scarring</strong> &mdash; raised, thick scars within wound boundaries.</li>
    <li><strong>Contractures</strong> &mdash; scar-tissue tightening across joints.</li>
    <li><strong>Chronic pain</strong> &mdash; including neuropathic pain in damaged dermal nerves.</li>
    <li><strong>Pruritus</strong> &mdash; severe itching in healing burns and mature scars; can be intractable.</li>
    <li><strong>Heterotopic ossification</strong> &mdash; abnormal bone growth in soft tissues; affects mobility.</li>
    <li><strong>Skin cancer</strong> &mdash; squamous cell carcinoma can arise in mature burn scars decades later.</li>
    <li><strong>PTSD and depression</strong> &mdash; high prevalence in moderate-to-severe burns.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>These complications inform the burn life-care plan and contribute to lifetime care costs.</p>

